# Complete IaaS Example

This guide walks through a single, complete configuration that provisions everything needed for a working, reachable VM on Nayatel Cloud: an SSH key, a private network, a security group, a compute instance, a data volume, and a floating IP. It also bootstraps a small HTTPS landing page so you have something to verify immediately after apply.

The full source lives at [`examples/main.tf`](https://github.com/matifali/terraform-provider-nayatel/blob/main/examples/main.tf) in the provider's GitHub repository.

## What it creates

- `nayatel_ssh_key` - registers an SSH key for instance access
- `nayatel_network` - a private network for the instance
- `nayatel_security_group` - opens SSH (22), HTTPS (443), and ICMP ping
- `nayatel_router` - connects the private network to the internet
- `nayatel_instance` - the VM itself, attached to the network
- `nayatel_security_group_attachment` - applies the security group to the instance
- `nayatel_volume` and `nayatel_volume_attachment` - an extra data volume, separate from the instance's root disk
- `nayatel_floating_ip` - a public IP attached to the instance
- An HTTPS bootstrap (`terraform_data` with a `remote-exec` provisioner) that installs nginx with a self-signed certificate, so `https://<floating-ip>` responds right after apply

All of the above (other than the SSH key, network, and security group) are gated behind `var.enable_compute_example`, so you can `terraform apply -var='enable_compute_example=false'` to try a lower-cost smoke test first.

## Usage

1. Set credentials (environment variables are recommended):

```shell
export NAYATEL_USERNAME="your-username"
export NAYATEL_PASSWORD="your-password"
```

2. Copy `examples/main.tf` into a working directory and initialize Terraform:

```shell
terraform init
```

3. If you keep `enable_https_bootstrap = true` (the default), make sure the private key matching `ssh_public_key` is loaded in your SSH agent:

```shell
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

4. Review the plan, then apply:

```shell
terraform plan
terraform apply
```

5. Once applied, the `ssh_command` and `https_url` outputs give you a ready-to-use command and URL:

```shell
terraform output ssh_command
terraform output https_url
```

6. When done, tear everything down:

```shell
terraform destroy
```

-> Nayatel router-interface detach can be unreliable, so this example sets `force_delete_network_on_destroy = true` on its router because it owns the disposable example network. Do not set that on a router attached to a shared or pre-existing network.

### No leaked resources after destroy

Destroying an instance also deletes its root volume by default (`delete_root_volume_on_destroy = true`), and the provider verifies the volume is actually gone — the Nayatel API has been observed to leave it behind, where it keeps billing with no way to remove it from the portal UI. If you ever delete an instance from the portal instead of Terraform, check your volume list afterwards: a leftover root volume shows up as a bootable volume named `default` with status `available`.

